up|52|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The 3@H was an interesting call. I would not have made the bid yet it had some merit. West could deduce we have a spade fit since partner has at most 4 spades and likely fewer. So by bidding 3@H West is making it harder for us to bid spades and in fact it may have worked. If West passes, then North might very well bid 2@S.|
PG| ***** 39 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2^^|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Should North bid 3@S over 3@H? That is less clear, although possible. The problem is, the person who is short in hearts has to compete. But West's strength is unknown. Therefore, bidding 3@S has some risk.|
PG| ***** 40 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2^^|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|It is likely we have a spade fit, but it is also possible we may get too high. I also could have stretched and bid 2N over 2@H. But at this vulnerability that is dangerous. So I passed. |
PG| ***** 41 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2^^|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now let's look at some alternatives to the current auction. If East opens 1@H, I probably pass. I could stretch and bid 1N but I only have 14, we are vul, and I am 4-3-3-3. So I probably pass.|
PG| ***** 42 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2^^|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|West presumably bids 1N. It is not clear what North should do, but let's assume pass is the call, particularly if 1N is forcing. North can come in with 2@S later to show long spades and a weak hand.|
PG| ***** 43 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2^^|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If North passes, East bids 2@H, I pass, and presumably West passes. Then North bids 2@S and East passes. Then it is not clear what should I do?|
PG| ***** 44 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2^^|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|We have at least an 8 card fit and very possibly 9. However, I know partner is weak since he didn't bid 2@S right away. Therefore, with my flat hand I could pass even though I am strong because based on the auction I know partner doesn't have enough for game.|
PG| ***** 45 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2^^|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Then West probably bids 3@H. So we might end up there, or I might choose to bid 3@S. Also, it is possible that many pairs would get to 3@S on this hand. In 3@S, if East leads a singleton club, we lose 2 clubs, a club ruff, and 2 diamonds at least. So at best we take 8 tricks.|
